{{#if resource.check}}
## Failed Check

**Check name**: {{resource.check.name}}
**Conclusion**: {{resource.check.conclusion}}
**Details URL**: {{resource.check.url}}
{{#if resource.check.output.title}}
**Output title**: {{resource.check.output.title}}
{{/if}}
{{#if resource.check.output.summary}}
**Output summary**:
{{resource.check.output.summary}}
{{/if}}

**Important**: This event was triggered by a FAILED CHECK. Before investigating:
- Identify the system that runs this check from the check name and details URL (e.g. GitHub Actions, CircleCI, Jenkins, a 3rd-party service)
- Check if there is an MCP server available that can interact with that system (e.g. a CI/CD MCP, test reporter MCP) — if so, use it to fetch detailed logs and failure context
- If no MCP server is available, fetch the details URL directly or use `gh` CLI to retrieve run logs
- Focus on fixing the root cause of the failure on the PR branch

{{/if}}

## Instructions

- Find the best Template according to Source Repository
- Create a sandbox using that Template with a name in the format "ai-<UUID>" — generate a random UUID (not human-readable, not derived from the issue/repo name), truncated to 16 characters max (sandbox name max length is 20)
- Target that sandbox and start working in the related workspace
  {{#if resource.comment}}
  - **This event was triggered by a comment** - Focus on addressing what was requested in the comment above
  - Fetch all previous comments for full context, but prioritize the new comment's request
  {{else}}
  - Fetch all comments and context related to this {{#eq type "pull_request"}}Pull Request{{else}}Issue{{/eq}} and understand the task accurately
  {{/if}}
  {{#if resource.author}}
  - When making commits, add the original issue/PR creator as a co-author if they are different from your committer identity:
    - Look up their name and email via `gh api /users/{{resource.author}}` or GitHub MCP `get_user`
    - If their email is not public, use `{{resource.author}}@users.noreply.github.com`
    - Add to every commit message: `Co-Authored-By: <Name> <<email>>`
    - **The co-author is always the original issue creator (`@{{resource.author}}`), not the person who triggered this event** (which may be a commenter)
  {{/if}}
  {{#eq type "pull_request"}}
  - Fetch all PR review comments (inline code review feedback on the diff) — prefer MCP tools (`pull_request_read` with `get_review_comments`) if available, otherwise fall back to `gh pr view --comments` — to understand all reviewer feedback before starting work
  - Make sure the branch related to this Pull Request is checked out
  - **This is an existing Pull Request — push changes ONLY to branch `{{resource.branch}}`. Do NOT create a new branch or a new PR.**
  - When pushing code:
    - Use standard git CLI: `git push origin {{resource.branch}}`
    - If that fails (e.g. authentication or permission errors), prefer GitHub MCP tools over raw API calls: use `push_files` or `create_or_update_file` to push file changes
  {{else}}
  - Checkout the correct remote branch from linked changes if any
  - When pushing code or creating a Pull Request:
    - Prefer standard git/gh CLI commands (`git push`, `gh pr create`, etc.)
    - If those fail (e.g. authentication or permission errors), prefer GitHub MCP tools over raw API calls:
      - Use `push_files` or `create_or_update_file` to push file changes
      - Use `create_pull_request` to open a new PR
      - Use `create_branch` to create a new branch
  {{/eq}}
  {{#if resource.assignees}}
  - If code change is required
    - Make the change according to what's required
    - Try the best effort to test and verify change in the sandbox by using any existing tests and performing additional tests when needed
    - Keep iterating until all tests and verification pass
    {{#eq type "pull_request"}}
    - Checkout the PR's branch: {{resource.branch}}
    - Address all open PR review comments (inline code feedback) as part of your changes
    - Commit and push the change to {{resource.branch}} - DO NOT create a new branch or a new PR
    - Add a comment to the Pull Request including:
      - A summary about the changes and test results
      - Which review comments were addressed
      - The sandbox name and template name (use "" if no template was used)
    - Resolve any PR review threads that your changes have addressed
    - DO NOT self-approve this Pull Request
    {{else}}
    - IMPORTANT: Check if this Issue explicitly asks to update an existing PR:
      * If YES (e.g., "update PR #456", "fix the PR", "modify the pull request"): Checkout that PR's branch and push changes there
      * If NO (new work, new feature, bug fix): Create a NEW unique branch name (e.g., "ai/issue-{{resource.number}}-<short-description>") - do NOT reuse existing branches
    - Commit and push the change to the appropriate remote branch
    - Create a Pull Request (or update existing if specified) and make sure:
      - Double check the default branch and do not assume
      {{#if resource.number}}{{#ne resource.number 0}}- Link back to the current Issue using the closing syntax (e.g., "Fixes #{{resource.number}}", "Closes #{{resource.number}}")
      {{/ne}}{{/if}}- Include this link in the PR description: {{resourceLink}}
      - The owner/assignee is yourself
      - Include a summary about the changes and test results
      - Include the sandbox name and template name (use "" if no template was used)
    - Add a comment to the {{#eq provider "slack"}}thread{{else}}Issue{{/eq}} with the same information as above
    {{/eq}}
  {{else}}
  - If code change is required
    - Make the change according to what's required
    - Try the best effort to test and verify change in the sandbox by using any existing tests and performing additional tests when needed
    - Keep iterating until all tests and verification pass
    {{#eq type "pull_request"}}
    - IMPORTANT: This is a comment on an existing PR requesting changes
      - Checkout the PR's branch: {{resource.branch}}
      - Address all open PR review comments (inline code feedback) as part of your changes
      - Make the requested changes on that branch
      - Commit and push to {{resource.branch}} to update this PR - DO NOT create a new branch or a new PR
      - Add a comment to the Pull Request with:
        - A summary about the changes and test results
        - Which review comments were addressed
        - The sandbox name and template name (use "" if no template was used)
      - Resolve any PR review threads that your changes have addressed
      - DO NOT approve
    {{else}}
    - IMPORTANT: Check if this Issue explicitly asks to update an existing PR:
      * If YES (e.g., "update PR #456", "fix the PR", "modify the pull request"): Checkout that PR's branch and push changes there
      * If NO (new work, new feature, bug fix): Create a NEW unique branch name (e.g., "ai/issue-{{resource.number}}-<short-description>") - do NOT reuse existing branches
    - Commit and push the change to the appropriate remote branch
    - Create a Pull Request (or update existing if specified) and make sure:
      {{#if resource.number}}{{#ne resource.number 0}}- Link back to the current Issue using the closing syntax (e.g., "Fixes #{{resource.number}}", "Closes #{{resource.number}}")
      {{/ne}}{{/if}}- Include this link in the PR description: {{resourceLink}}
      - The owner/assignee is yourself
      - Include a summary about the changes and test results
      - Include the sandbox name and template name (use "" if no template was used)
    - Add a comment to the {{#eq provider "slack"}}thread{{else}}Issue{{/eq}} with the same information as above
    {{/eq}}
  {{#eq type "pull_request"}}
  - If code review is required
    - Explore the codebase to find guidelines for reviewing the code
    - Review the code after common good practices and any guidelines found in the codebase
    - Test and verify the change using any existing tests and performing additional tests when needed
    - If any existing test failed, decide whether the change needs fix or the test should be updated due to requirement change
    - Add a comment with comprehensive report of review and testing
    - Approve the Pull Request when everything is good
  {{/eq}}
  {{/if}}

  - If the task requires code analysis or understanding:
    - Add a comment to the {{#eq type "pull_request"}}Pull Request{{else}}Issue{{/eq}} with a report of the analysis
